content.description: Thin climbing to a mid-height crux.  Feet are the key here.  A couple steep moves on big holds at the top.  Chains and biners at the top.
content.protection: Well-bolted, chains at top.
content.location: The right-hand line on the slabby face to the right of the Secret Agent Man pillar.

content.description:
The first route encountered when arriving at the Qual Wall from the Horse trail. 

  Follows a line of bolts up the face and takes the rightward line when bolts split at halfway.  Continue up to the sweeping headwall for the bouldery crux.
content.protection: 11 bolts to chain anchor. Shares first 4 bolts with Mean and Green.
content.location: First route, take right variation.

content.description: This is a dirty short route that is sledom climbed.
content.protection: Standard rack

content.description:
Tramadol: A narcotic for moderate to severe pain, with a high risk for addiction... Far right on the warm up wall, this "two" pitch route is quite unique for Wisconsin, providing a multi pitch opportunity for the novice climber to become addicted or to simply link the pitches, which keeps the pain away.

 Pitch one climbs up the short, small right facing dihedral found above the water grooved, weathered rocked. A few perfect jugs, and crimps to the ledge above. Pitch two leaves the flat belay ledge and up a few more bolts on the fluted rock to the highest point of the wall.

 Pitch one variation, start low and right of the first bolt and continue right of the bolt line to rejoin the route at bolt #3 for a 5.10- experience. Stick clipping the first bolt is highly recommended.
content.protection: Bolted.  *(edited 5/17/21) Per DH, it was originally climbed as a trad line back in the day. My apologies for bolting a trad line, this goes against my personal ethics if I would have known at the time.
content.location: Right side of warm up wall.

content.description: From Huston's topo:   A few pins remain as signs of previous passage.   Toprope off of the upper chains of A Red Recollection to ensure safe passage.   Grade is a total guess as of this posting.
content.protection: Top Rope and pins? Leadable?
content.location: Between "Red Recollection" and "Secret Agent Man".

content.description: Classic highball for the park. Start in pit on obvious right hand sloper sidepull and left hand a little lower in the crack. Climb the arete through some nice holds. Trend a bit left as you near the top and finish to the left of the mushroom cap. Crux is low, top is easy but pumpy.
content.protection: 3 pads minimum.
content.location: In a big pit on the backside of the Qual wall. Anchors for SAM are very close.

content.description: Problem located below the left side of the sport cliff. Turn left on a trail just before the end of the cliff. The boulder is 20 feet down this trail on the left hand side. Can't miss it. Start on two mini jugs, go up right to a sloper, and straight up through another jug and undercling to the lip. Top out straight up over the lip.

A nice boulder for warming up or if you didn't bring a pad. Sit start at the bottom of the funnel and traverse right into the bear cave. Follow the continuing overhang to ledge. This is a low traverse boulder. Maybe someone will send a vertical boulder here but the landing is seriously sloped and pretty janky.
content.location: In the pit behind the Qual Wall. Walk South and around to the backside of the Qual Wall, continue to the balanced rock on top of the wall over a funnel.

content.description: The the most difficult of the warmups, and it looks better than it climbs. Fun climbing though, with an assortment of holds. You can’t miss the large pockets. Shares anchors with Leftwing.
content.protection: 4 Bolts to chains. Anchor is shared with Leftwing.
content.location: Warm up wall, second route from left.

content.description: Far right bolted line on warm up wall. Kind of jacked.
content.protection: Bolts to chains. Shared first bolt and anchors with Slab Me Harder.
content.location: Warm up wall

content.description: Fourth route from the left hand side.
content.protection: Bolts to chains. Shared first bolt and anchor with Slab Right
content.location: Fourth route from left hand side of wall.

content.description: Alongside the super classic Whiskey a Go-Go at Necedah, Secret Agent Man, has over the last couple decades, become a must do 5.13- sport route in Southern Wisconsin. This stunning face/arête line easily has some of the best rock in the Dodge, however, if you have spent much time walking cliff bands in the park, you know this wall is the 1% as far as roped climbing goes.Start up big moves on good edges and arête, then enter the short lived little dihedral. Work out left past a small bulgy boulder problem to gain an adequate shake above. Stay focused, and stay on the line, then launch into a series of breathtaking boulder problems stacked on top of each other on the left side of the sweeping, overhanging arête.
content.protection: 7 bolts to chain anchors.
content.location: Hard to miss. Sweeping arête.

content.description:
This is a sweet problem that climbs a cool hanging block with an amazing iron band/tufa around the left end of the Qual Wall. It's a nice boulder to hit on your way back from warming up at the Lonelies.

 Start on a jug in the break under the block, and climb out on to the face using amazing iron band crimps, then bust out left to the arete.  Head up the arete, then move back right to top out.
content.protection: Pads and spotters.  The landing is tiered, but can be flattened out nicely with enough pads.  A spotter on the ledge will keep you safe for the crux moves.
content.location: Around the left end of the Qual Wall.  Follow the trail as for the Lonely Boulders, but as you start to head north, look to your right.  Quality Control is the large hanging block, with a distinctive diagonal iron band on the upper face.

content.description: Climb "Warm up 1" to it's third bolt (Warm up 1 crux). Then angle leftward through "Warm up 2" (clip 3rd bolt of Warm up 2, climb up and execute Warm up 2 crux). Next traverse across horizontal break into "Nut Job" (1-2 pieces of gear. execute Nut job crux). Traverse left just below the small roof and finish on the last two bolts of "Pocket Warmup" (crux of "Pocket warmup" and crux of entire link-up).   A fun warm up and a nice way to make for a longer pitch on a somewhat short wall...
content.protection: Bolts + 1-2 small cams for Nut Job.
content.location: Slab routes

content.description: If other routes are occupied or too hard try this moderate TR.
content.protection: TR, webbing.
content.location: Located right of the two slab routes. One technical move to the low angle mossy slab to the base of a 40 ft wall. Cool features await you.

content.description: Perhaps the most enjoyable climbing on the wall, Nut Job is great warm up if you are confident at the grade. Named for the plethora of wired nut placements found along the route. Follow the obvious thin crack line in the center of the wall through jugs, and a few jams out featured rock. One bolt up high.
content.protection: Wires and cams. The protection looks good, but this rock is always suspect. If there is any question about wether or not you could lead this on gear, just don't. Easily toproped from anchors on right...
content.location: Warm up wall, Center

content.description: The left line of bolts on the S.A.M. pillar, Now or Never traverses up and left with very cool moves from near the start of a Red Recollection.  Crimpy moves take you up the steep face.  It's definitely harder (12a/b?) to stay on the face and avoid the jugs to the left.  Most stop at the first set of anchors over the bulge (same anchors for Red Recollection).
content.protection: Bolts.  Please inspect bolts and use your judgement, as always, while climbing.
content.location: To the left of A Red Recollection.

content.description: From Huston's topo:Start up the first three bolts of Secret Agent Man before stepping to right around arete and charging up the steep north face. Better than it looks.
content.protection: 9 bolts, chains with steel biners at the top.
content.location: Starts up SAM and then steps around arete to the inside face.

content.description: This was sandy, dirty, and a real bitch to set up on TR. I believe there was someone who once said "Why? Why not?"
content.protection: LONG slings from a nice tree up top.
content.location: When the trail come to the wall go right instead of left. This is an ugly looking arete. The route pretty much ends at the high bulging roof with seemingly no holds to go higher.

content.description: Mean and Green climbs the left hand version of the two routes on the first tall golden wall. They share the first 4 bolts. Crux at about 2/3 height leads to some amazing jugs up high. The quality can vary quite a bit on this route but a fun outing if you are not too offended by choss.
content.protection: 9 bolts with 2 chain anchors. Shares first 4 bolts with Meaner than Green.
content.location: First wall you come to when walking up the trail from the horse trail.

content.description: Start on a good undercling and bump your way up to a gaston. Turn it into a sidepull and top out left using one small hidden crimp on the ramp.
content.protection: pad, flat landing
content.location: Not at the Lonely Boulders per se, this problem is at the Qual Wall (on the way to the Lonlies).  On the belay ledge for S.A.M, this would be the wall to the right that most people lean against while watching someone on S.A.M.  Just to the right of the start for Unlisted Number.

content.description:
Perhaps the most enjoyable 5.10 on the warmup wall, with a liberal grade. This route features fun, technical climbing on pretty good features. A few awkward moves at the crux detracts from the overall quality, but still a worthy route to get the blood moving.

 You can easily TR Sobriety Test or hang draws.
content.protection: 4 Bolts to chains. Anchor is shared with Sobriety Test.
content.location: Warm Up wall, left side

content.description: From Huston's topo:   A top rope to the left of Now Or Never. Steep moves over an overhang down low lead to an arête above.
content.protection: Top Rope.
content.location: Left of "Now or Never".

content.description: Possibly the most underappreciated, if not downright overlooked, cracks in Wisconsin. I am astonished that this has not been developed or heavily climbed in the last 10 years. This overhanging crack climb contains some of the most prolonged, secure, well-protected trad climbing in the area, but be prepared to work for it. Start out with somewhat heady and insecure for the grade, face and arete moves on the same line as More Choss than Moss. Upon reaching the overhanging wall, traverse right and continue up the obvious crack in the corner using great hand jams and stemming feet. The crux for me was the awkward mantle about 3/4 of the way up the route. Continue up the rest of the crack system and build an anchor on large ledge (or be prepared for a long runout and serious rope drag)."Get a horse!", as shouted to us by one of the horseback riders upon seeing us hauling our gear up the trail, accurately describes the feeling after topping out this climb. This is fantastic crack climbing that will work you in a relatively short distance, with very few breakable holds for how untouched the rock has been in recent years.
content.protection: Standard Rack. Small nut and cam placements low. Bigger Cams and Hexes in the crack.For toprope use LONG slings or static line from good tree at top. On lead use low toprope anchor, or deal with a lot of runout and rope drag after finishing the route. We did a 5.0ish second pitch to walk off the top.
content.location: Far Climber's Right on Quall Wall. Shares same start as 'More Choss than Moss'.

content.description: From Huston's topo:   Boulder through the first three bolts (crux), shake out, and then continue up the wall above avoiding the chimney on your left. The grade is unconfirmed. Shares the final two bolts and chains with the previous route.
content.protection: Bolts to chains. Shares anchors with Unlisted Number.
content.location: Left route on slab to the right of "Secret Agent Man".

content.description: Climb to the upper anchors of Red Recollection (clip with long sling), climb right, clip the last bolt of Secret Agent Man, and fire the final ~V3 crux leading to the anchors of Secret Agent Man. Of course, don't stop until you top out Secret Agent Man (only clipping the chains below the lip invalidates the ascent, you know).    A 007 way to clip the anchors of a great 13a. Also a good warm up...
content.protection: ~9 bolts

content.description: Directly left of Leftwing is a fairly parallel-sided crack. Stem up the bottom, then pull around a bulge before squeezing through the crack to finish. Abundant face holds and feet make it a comfortable lead.
content.protection: Bring a #3 Camalot and some larger pro. A #4 might also be desirable?
content.location: Start directly left of Leftwing.

content.description: This route climbs the large hanging block between The Nordwand and Fahrenheit 23.  To start, climb the somewhat chossy chimney/inset to a good ledge in the left chimney near The Nordwand.  This is where the climbing really begins and becomes quite good.  From the ledge, there should be a small edge on the face of the block - grab this, establish on the face and start slapping up the block.  And keep slapping, heel hooking, and toe hooking until one can reach the perfect jug at the top of the block.  The actual hanging block is some of the best rock at the Dodge, but this is unfortunatly an eliminate (don't use the Fahrenheit 23 wall!) and merely a toprope.  None-the-less it is exceptionally unique climbing and a lot of fun.
content.protection: Toprope.  Bring a couple long slings to tie off a huge tree at the top of the route.
content.location: Located on the block between The Nordwand and Fahrenheit 23.

content.description:
The year was 1996. Slick Willie was president. The Macarena was sweeping the nation. The internet was a torture device. And the U.S. sport climbing scene was still in it’s wild and rebellious adolescence. After a six month road trip of some the best sport crags in the nation at that time, Seth and I came back to Wisconsin with a whole new perspective on life. A Red Recollection was the first line we established here for obvious reasons, and it is named after the Red River Gorge, which I thought had the best sport climbing I'd ever seen.

 The line climbs the center of the wall up a unique "tufaesque" layback feature for thirty feet with awesome non technical stemming. The crux seems to come all too soon and involves a thought provoking bulge, which is passed on the left. Continue up to your choice of low, or high anchor.
content.protection: Sport Anchor over the bulge for original pitch, or continue to the second set if you wish which adds climbing, but nothing to the grade per se. Cleaning the pitch on TR is probably the way to go.
content.location: Center line on the wall. Starts off of an awesome flat boulder.

content.description: A sport climbing area on a small cliff band. The sandstone is generally solid with crimpers and slopers predominating. A topo prepared by Jason Huston is available below. At this time there is no further bolting of routes allowed.  MINIGUIDE TO QUAL WALLhttps://www.scribd.com/document/74534847/Qual-Wall-Topo
